FOREGROUND SERVICE ‚Äì COMPLETE NOTES
===============================

--------------------------------
WHAT IS A FOREGROUND SERVICE?
--------------------------------
A Foreground Service is a type of Android Service that:
- Runs in the background
- MUST display a persistent notification
- Has higher priority than normal background services
- Is less likely to be killed by the system

It tells the system:
üëâ ‚ÄúThe user is actively aware of this task, do not stop it.‚Äù

--------------------------------
KEY CHARACTERISTICS
--------------------------------
‚Ä¢ Runs even when app is minimized or closed
‚Ä¢ Always shows a notification
‚Ä¢ User can see and control it
‚Ä¢ High priority in system memory
‚Ä¢ Requires FOREGROUND_SERVICE permission
‚Ä¢ Uses startForeground() method

--------------------------------
WHEN TO USE FOREGROUND SERVICE?
--------------------------------
Use Foreground Service when:

‚úî Task is important to user
‚úî Task must continue even if app is closed
‚úî Task should not be killed by system
‚úî User must be informed that task is running

--------------------------------
WHY TO USE FOREGROUND SERVICE?
--------------------------------
‚Ä¢ Normal background services are restricted (Android 8+)
‚Ä¢ System may kill background tasks anytime
‚Ä¢ Foreground Service guarantees execution
‚Ä¢ Mandatory for long-running tasks

--------------------------------
COMMON USE CASES
--------------------------------
‚Ä¢ Music playback
‚Ä¢ GPS / Location tracking
‚Ä¢ File download / upload
‚Ä¢ Fitness tracking
‚Ä¢ Screen recording
‚Ä¢ Call recording
‚Ä¢ Data synchronization
‚Ä¢ Navigation apps (Google Maps)

--------------------------------
FOREGROUND SERVICE LIFECYCLE
--------------------------------
1. startForegroundService()
2. onCreate()
3. onStartCommand()
4. startForeground(notification)
5. Service runs
6. stopService() OR stopSelf()
7. onDestroy()
8. Notification removed

--------------------------------
IMPORTANT METHODS
--------------------------------
‚Ä¢ startForegroundService()
  ‚Üí Starts foreground service

‚Ä¢ startForeground(id, notification)
  ‚Üí Promotes service to foreground

‚Ä¢ stopForeground(true)
  ‚Üí Removes notification

‚Ä¢ stopSelf()
  ‚Üí Stops service internally

--------------------------------
PERMISSION REQUIRED
--------------------------------
<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.FOREGROUND_SERVICE"/>

(Android 13+ may need additional permissions like location, media, etc.)

--------------------------------
FOREGROUND vs BACKGROUND vs BOUND SERVICE
--------------------------------



--------------------------------
ADVANTAGES
--------------------------------
‚Ä¢ Reliable execution
‚Ä¢ High system priority
‚Ä¢ User transparency
‚Ä¢ Suitable for critical tasks
‚Ä¢ Works even in low-memory situations

--------------------------------
DISADVANTAGES
--------------------------------
‚Ä¢ Mandatory notification (can annoy users)
‚Ä¢ Battery consumption
‚Ä¢ Overuse may lead to bad UX
‚Ä¢ Play Store policy restrictions

--------------------------------
ANDROID VERSION NOTES
--------------------------------
‚Ä¢ Android 8+ ‚Üí Background services restricted
‚Ä¢ Foreground Service preferred
‚Ä¢ Android 10+ ‚Üí Foreground service type required
‚Ä¢ Android 13+ ‚Üí More strict permissions

--------------------------------
BEST PRACTICES
--------------------------------
‚úî Use only when necessary
‚úî Stop service when task finishes
‚úî Provide meaningful notification
‚úî Don‚Äôt misuse for background work
‚úî Respect user privacy

--------------------------------
EXAM ONE-LINER
--------------------------------
"A Foreground Service is an Android service that performs long-running tasks
while showing a persistent notification to the user."

--------------------------------
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
--------------------------------
"Foreground Services are used for user-visible, high-priority background tasks
that must continue even when the app is not in the foreground."

